### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

compiler

### Is this a regression?

Yes

### Description

I just generated a new Angular application and created two libraries, `lib-a` & `lib-b`

For a better developer experience, I updated the tsconfig `paths` to point to the source code so updates to the libraries will cause application recompliation:

```
    "paths": {
      "lib-a": [
        "./projects/lib-a/src/public-api"
      ],
      "lib-b": [
        "./projects/lib-b/src/public-api"
      ]
    },
```

I injected `LibAService` into the application

```
import { Component } from '@angular/core';
import { RouterOutlet } from '@angular/router';
import { LibAService } from 'lib-a';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  imports: [RouterOutlet],
  templateUrl: './app.component.html',
  styleUrl: './app.component.css'
})
export class AppComponent {
  title = 'paths-bug';

  constructor(libAService: LibAService) {}
}
```

I then injected `LibBService` into `lib-a`

```
import { Injectable } from '@angular/core';
import { LibBService } from 'lib-b';

@Injectable({
  providedIn: 'root'
})
export class LibAService {

  constructor(libBService: LibBService) {

    console.log('LibAService constructor!!!!');
   }
}
```

Serving and building the application works fine as expected, but now trying to build `lib-a` I receive the following error:

`Cannot destructure property 'pos' of 'file.referencedFiles[index]' as it is undefined.`

It appears that changing the tsconfig `paths` to point to the TypeScript source is the cause of this issue - but why? Shouldn't we be able to compile Angular libs with `paths` pointing to source?


